# Terminal Option Documentation for Bun.spawn

## Overview

You can spawn a subprocess with a pseudo-terminal (PTY) using the `terminal` option, enabling interactive terminal features like colored output and cursor movement.

## Basic Usage

```ts
const proc = Bun.spawn(["bash"], {
  terminal: {
    cols: 80,
    rows: 24,
    data(terminal, data) {
      // Called when data is received from the terminal
      process.stdout.write(data);
    },
  },
});

proc.terminal.write("echo hello\n");
await proc.exited;
proc.terminal.close();
```

## Data Callback

The `data` callback is invoked "when data is received from the terminal." You can handle output by processing the incoming data:

```ts
data(terminal, data) {
  process.stdout.write(data);
}
```

## setRawMode Method

The Terminal object provides a method to "set raw mode (disable line buffering and echo)":

```ts
proc.terminal.setRawMode(true);
```

This allows disabling automatic line buffering and character echo, useful for interactive applications requiring direct control over terminal behavior.

## Terminal Options Table

| Option | Purpose | Default |
|--------|---------|---------|
| `cols` | Number of columns | `80` |
| `rows` | Number of rows | `24` |
| `name` | Terminal type for PTY | `"xterm-256color"` |
| `data` | Callback for incoming data | — |
| `exit` | Callback when PTY closes | — |
| `drain` | Callback when ready for more data | — |

**Note:** Terminal support is only available on POSIX systems (Linux, macOS), not Windows.

